  <h2 class="title"> 1</h2>
The male would think as follows:

<p>	  Route B3 seems very alluring to me because it would give me altitudes of 2239m, 2950m, 3152m and 1875m. I would love to be at the top Piz Boe at 3152m because it is one of the spectacular of the Sella Group. However, if I choose this route, and she chooses the route G4, we would actually camp at the junction of 1875m (Passo Campolongo) and this altitude is unbreathable to me. I would not risk choosing B3.
</p>
	  <img src="https://c10.patreonusercontent.com/3/eyJ3IjoxMjQwfQ%3D%3D/patreon-media/p/post/15926625/69aa1ff121e8463285e4a56b3c6e100f/1.jpg?token-time=1557014400&token-hash=RU7u5bbO0dqcJggw2VTNcz84hCnhlHLyowXVPdaD86s%3D">


<p>	  So he starts to use the same criterion to look at other routes. For each route, he circles the lowest point. In route B1, the lowest point is 2136m. In route B2, the lowest point is 2200m. In route B3, the lowest point is 1875m.
</p>
<p>
Now among these lowest points, he notices that the point 2200m is the highest. So it is the highest point among the lowest points. Which means that Route B2 gives the highest of the lowest points. He finds B2 to be a safe route to choose, in the case his partner wants to get as low as possible.
</p>
</article>

