	  She would start by looking at each separate route and identify the highest point possible that the route offers. She wants to enjoy the affair without dying. The highest point of route G1 is 2848m. The highest point of route G2 is 2953m. The highest point of route G3 is 3152m. The highest point of route G4 is 2200m. She circles all the highest points of each route.

Among these highest points, she notices that the lowest point is 2200m and this belongs to route G4. For her, the route G4 provides a safe route because the highest her partner can make her camp is at 2200m. If she chooses other routes, her partner can make her to camp higher and she would not want to risk that. So she feels route G4 to be safe.
</article>

<article class="tile is-child notification is-light">
<h2 class="title">3</h2>

We can see that, with this kind of reasoning for both sides, they would end up choosing route B2 and route G4 and they end up camping at 2200m (Lago Boe). Peace.
</article>
<article class="tile is-child notification is-light">
<h2 class="title">4</h2>

This example illustrates the core of von Neumann thinking: you would want to choose in the way that, even when your opponent hates you, you can still have the best of the worst they want to inflict on you. 

Using the language of game theory, two hikers are two players because they are interested in different things. They have distinct interests. Otherwise they would have been considered one player, even though they are two persons. And the altitude corresponds to their enjoyment, which is called the payoff. Higher altitude means higher payoff to the male, and it means lower payoff to the female.

We interpret again the above thinking: 

    Because your opponent want to minimise your payoff, you want to maximise among the minimal payoffs they can give you. 

And this is where the word maxi-min comes from. Maximin strategy is one of the legacy of von Neumann for game theory. Another word to describe this situation is a saddle point. It is a saddle point because it feels like the surface of a saddle: the boy is reaching the minimum from one side and the girl is reaching the maximum from an other side.

Another thing to note is that this is a zero sum game:

    A zero sum game is a game in which the interests of the two players directly oppose each other. 

In our example, the higher he is, the lower she feels and vice versa. This is another main contribution of von Neumann to early game theory. To the point that if you say zero sum game, you mean the game theory of von Neumann. Another example of a zero sum game that explains better the word zero sum is chess. In chess, if White wins then Black loses and vice versa. Let's say White wins and gets the payoff (reward) of 1 unit of prize. Then it simultaneously means that Black loses and gets the payoff of -1. Or we can say that Black has to pay out 1 unit of prize, in this case, Black pays to White 1 unit. 1 + (- 1) = 0 hence this is called the zero sum game.
